  "prompt": "LIGO uses laser light, but why are the lasers not altered by the gravitational waves?",
  "response": "LIGO (Laser Interferometer Gravitational-Wave Observatory) uses lasers to detect gravitational waves, but the lasers themselves are not directly altered by the gravitational waves. Here\u2019s why:\n\n### 1. **Gravitational Waves Affect Spacetime, Not Light Directly**\n   - Gravitational waves are ripples in spacetime itself, causing distortions in the fabric of space as they pass through. These distortions affect the distances between objects (like the mirrors in LIGO\u2019s interferometers) but do not directly alter the properties of the laser light (such as its wavelength or frequency).\n   - The laser light itself is just a tool to measure the changes in distance caused by the gravitational waves.\n\n### 2. **LIGO Measures Changes in Path Length, Not Light Properties**\n   - LIGO\u2019s interferometers work by splitting a laser beam into two perpendicular arms, bouncing the beams off mirrors, and then recombining them. When a gravitational wave passes through, it slightly changes the lengths of the arms (on the order of 1/10,000th the width of a proton). This change in path length causes a phase shift in the recombined light, which is detected as an interference pattern.\n   - The laser\u2019s properties (like its wavelength) remain constant; it\u2019s the path length that changes.\n\n### 3. **Laser Light is Highly Stable**\n   - LIGO uses extremely stable lasers with a constant wavelength and frequency. The gravitational waves are far too weak to affect the laser\u2019s emission process or the photons themselves.\n\n### 4. **Gravitational Waves are Extremely Weak**\n   - The strains caused by gravitational waves are incredibly small (on the order of \\(10^{-21}\\) or less). Such tiny distortions have no measurable effect on the laser light itself but can be detected through the changes in the interferometer\u2019s arm lengths.\n\n### 5. **Interferometry Detects Relative Changes**\n   - The key to LIGO\u2019s sensitivity is measuring the relative phase shift of the laser light in the two arms of the interferometer. The gravitational wave affects the lengths of the arms differently, creating a detectable difference in the light\u2019s travel time.\n\nIn summary, the lasers in LIGO are not altered by gravitational waves because the waves affect spacetime (changing distances) rather than the properties of the light. The laser light is simply a precise tool for measuring these minute changes in distance.",
